@wordwrap

@node Main "Layouter V1.1"
                               @{" < Table of contents " link "Macro-Package.guide/Main"}

@{fg shine}Benifits:@{fg text}
   When you change of the Page format from Tall to Wide (and vice versa)
   £Final Writer¨ uses the same edit area format left stays left, to stays top.
   Some times you want top to be the top of the paper when you print it.
   However, you can manually alter the editor area.

   The manual rearrangement, is difficult out to do.
   "Layouter" helps you by rearranging the editor area for you.
   So Left is the Left side of the pager, as it comes out of the printer,
   and Top is the top side of the paper, as it comes out of the printer.

@{fg shine}Requirements:@{fg text}
   None.

@{fg shine}Using the @{"macro" system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview Layouter.iff"}:@{fg text}

   C@{fg fill}h@{fg text}ange
      This is the same as selecting the Menu: Layout | Page
      After you have changed the page side or Format a question will be
      posed to you: Do you mant to alter the edit area

      - automaticaly: The Edit area will be automaticaly altered for the new
                      format.
      - manually:     You alter it your self.

   Edit Area
      When you start the Macro the current settings for the edit area are
      automatically entered.
      From here you can edit the settings for the Edit Area.
      There are 4 fields @{fg fill}T@{fg text}op, @{fg fill}B@{fg text}ottom, @{fg fill}L@{fg text}eft and @{fg fill}R@{fg text}ight
      These fields are as the Page comes out of the printer NOT as on the
      screen.
      Put simply : In Wide format is TOP on the page LEFT,
                   or as it comes out of the printer TOP.

                     - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - 

   @{fg fill}A@{fg text}pply
      The Edit Area will be altered as you stated above.
      When using "automatic" alteration, you don not need to use this button.

   @{fg fill}C@{fg text}ancel
   @{fg fill}ESC@{fg text} or closing the window
      Terminates the macro.

@endnode
